  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "We designed an ablation approach (termed the cumulative inactivation procedure (CLIP)) to identify which model LCs contributed the most to each behavioural output.",
    "The first step in CLIP is to inactivate each model LC unit individually by setting a model LC's activity value for all time frames to a constant value (chosen to be the mean activity value across all frames).",
    "We found that setting the activity to 0 (as we do during knockout training) obscures nuanced but important relationships because a value of 0 may be far from the working regime of activity for a given stimulus, resulting in large deviations in predicted output.",
    "Instead, we focus on how variation in a model LC unit's response contributes to variations in predicted behaviour.",
    "We test to what extent the 1-to-1 network with the inactivated model LC unit predicts the behavioural output of held-out test data from control flies (from the test set)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}